And because of that, if there are adjacent r-groups which have their bonding orbitals

224
00:18:13,000 --> 00:18:19,600
aligned with that pi system, the electrons from the adjacent bond can participate with

225
00:18:19,600 --> 00:18:24,400
the pi electrons, giving a larger system through which they can move.

226
00:18:24,400 --> 00:18:30,160
And we all know that when you extend the region through which electrons can move, you increase

227
00:18:30,160 --> 00:18:35,760
the stability of the species.

228
00:18:35,760 --> 00:18:41,240
Now Zetzev used an alcohol dehydration reaction, which we're going to look at in a future lecture,

229
00:18:41,240 --> 00:18:47,240
to demonstrate that alkenes of higher substitution are indeed more stable.

230
00:18:47,240 --> 00:18:50,960
Zetzev needed to use this system because, frankly, it was one of the very few understood

231
00:18:50,960 --> 00:18:53,040
reactions in his day.

232
00:18:53,040 --> 00:18:59,920
But this part of the story is going to have to wait for another lecture.

233
00:18:59,920 --> 00:19:04,760
Modern chemists can much more easily verify Zetzev's conclusions.

234
00:19:04,760 --> 00:19:11,880
Today we often compare the stability of unsaturated hydrocarbons using the technique of calorimetry.

235
00:19:11,880 --> 00:19:15,920
Remember that in a calorimetry experiment, a reaction is allowed to run to completion

236
00:19:15,920 --> 00:19:19,440
in a closed, well-insulated vessel.

237
00:19:19,440 --> 00:19:23,560
And the temperature of the contents is then monitored.

238
00:19:23,560 --> 00:19:27,640
On completion of the reaction, the amount of chemical potential energy gained or lost

239
00:19:27,640 --> 00:19:32,320
by the reacting molecules is proportional to the temperature change of the surroundings

240
00:19:32,320 --> 00:19:34,720
within the calorimeter.

241
00:19:34,720 --> 00:19:40,040
Take our example of the two structural isomers of butene, the simplest alkene to have both

242
00:19:40,040 --> 00:19:42,720
structural isomers and stereoisomers.

243
00:19:43,720 --> 00:19:49,480
It's obvious that one butene is unique from two butene, and that one butene has only a

244
00:19:49,480 --> 00:19:55,520
single stereoisomer because one of its alkene carbons has two hydrogen substituents.

245
00:19:55,520 --> 00:20:00,920
Two butene, however, can exist in two different stereoisomeric states.

246
00:20:00,920 --> 00:20:05,480
But which of these three isomers is most stable, and how can we tell?

247
00:20:05,480 --> 00:20:10,280
If we want to compare the relative stability of several related alkenes, we can simply

248
00:20:10,320 --> 00:20:15,560
convert samples of each molecule into their saturated counterparts in a calorimeter using

249
00:20:15,560 --> 00:20:20,680
a reaction known as hydrogenation.

250
00:20:20,680 --> 00:20:26,920
Hydrogenation is a process which saturates alkenes and alkynes using hydrogen gas.

251
00:20:26,920 --> 00:20:32,760
Essentially we're trading two hydrogen atoms for each pi bond in the starting material.

252
00:20:32,760 --> 00:20:37,180
We investigate the details of how and why this reaction happens during our lecture on

253
00:20:37,180 --> 00:20:42,440
addition reactions, but for now let's just focus on the starting materials in the products.

254
00:20:42,440 --> 00:20:46,060
Take a look at all three hydrogenation reactions.

255
00:20:46,060 --> 00:20:52,500
They all start with one mole of alkene, one mole of hydrogen, and end with the exact same

256
00:20:52,500 --> 00:20:56,300
product, butane.

257
00:20:56,300 --> 00:21:01,500
Because the only difference among the reactions is the identity of the alkene, any difference

258
00:21:01,500 --> 00:21:06,500
in the amount of heat released in the reaction must be a reflection of the differences in

259
00:21:06,500 --> 00:21:09,440
the free energies of those alkenes.

260
00:21:09,440 --> 00:21:15,100
In other words, hydrogenation of less stable alkenes releases more heat, causing a greater

261
00:21:15,100 --> 00:21:19,980
temperature change in the calorimeter.

262
00:21:19,980 --> 00:21:23,960
Conducting our simple calorimetry experiment gives us great insight into the factors affecting

263
00:21:23,960 --> 00:21:25,980
alkene stability.

264
00:21:25,980 --> 00:21:31,740
An equal quantity of one butene releases more heat when hydrogenated, which validates Zetzev's

265
00:21:31,740 --> 00:21:33,480
rule.

266
00:21:33,480 --> 00:21:38,480
We also see that not only is Zetzev's rule validated, but the geometric arrangement

267
00:21:38,480 --> 00:21:45,320
of larger substituents also appears to affect stability somewhat, with E2 butene being more

268
00:21:45,320 --> 00:21:50,360
stable than Z2 butene.

269
00:21:50,360 --> 00:21:56,280
The difference in stability between the E and Z isomers is usually attributed to sterics,

270
00:21:56,280 --> 00:22:02,200
that is, the physical proximity of substituent electron clouds in the molecule, placing two

271
00:22:02,200 --> 00:22:08,760
larger alkyl substituents closer to one another as in the Z isomer, causes a natural repulsion

272
00:22:08,760 --> 00:22:15,120
which is not present when those substituents are at opposition in the E isomer.

273
00:22:15,120 --> 00:22:21,120
Not surprisingly, internal alkenes also prove more stable than their external counterparts.

274
00:22:21,120 --> 00:22:26,040
So we see the same trend that Zetzev would predict for internal and terminal alkenes,

275
00:22:26,040 --> 00:22:33,840
though the linear geometry of these compounds precludes any geometric isomerism.

276
00:22:33,840 --> 00:22:38,160
So let's return now to our introductory story.

277
00:22:38,160 --> 00:22:42,640
What goes on chemically when your eyes are overexposed to light?

278
00:22:42,640 --> 00:22:47,160
Or for that matter, when your eyes are exposed to normal levels of light?

279
00:22:47,160 --> 00:22:53,000
The rods and cones in your eyes contain specific molecules which interact with light.

280
00:22:53,000 --> 00:22:56,920
We call molecules like this chromophores.

281
00:22:56,920 --> 00:23:03,320
The chromophore responsible for your vision is called retinol, and it looks like this.

282
00:23:03,320 --> 00:23:08,840
Now retinol has a number of alkene groups, all of which we know from our earlier calorimetry

283
00:23:08,840 --> 00:23:16,280
data should be most stable when in the trans or E configuration.

284
00:23:16,280 --> 00:23:22,560
But the retinol in your eyes has one double bond in the cis or Z-confirmation.

285
00:23:22,560 --> 00:23:27,400
It's locked in this way because of the pi bond on the 11th carbon of the chain.

286
00:23:27,400 --> 00:23:34,320
So this 11-cis retinol wants to be all trans retinol, but it can't get there without some

287
00:23:34,320 --> 00:23:37,500
help.

288
00:23:37,500 --> 00:23:41,440
The help comes in the form of photons, light.

289
00:23:41,440 --> 00:23:46,440
When a photon of appropriate energy strikes the retinol molecule, breaking just the pi

290
00:23:46,440 --> 00:23:54,400
bond on the 11th carbon, sterics calls the C11-C12 bond to rotate before re-establishing

291
00:23:54,400 --> 00:23:59,320
the pi bond in the more stable trans configuration.

292
00:23:59,320 --> 00:24:05,320
This change in the shape of retinol, promoted by absorption of light, induces a conformational

293
00:24:05,320 --> 00:24:08,800
change in a protein to which it's bound.

294
00:24:08,800 --> 00:24:13,920
And this starts a cascade of electrochemical signaling which your brain ultimately interprets

295
00:24:14,000 --> 00:24:18,260
as vision.

296
00:24:18,260 --> 00:24:24,000
An enzyme known as retinol isomerase then resets the alkene bond in retinol to the higher

297
00:24:24,000 --> 00:24:30,340
energy, 11-cis-confirmation, making it ready to detect light again.

298
00:24:30,340 --> 00:24:35,680
This process takes a little bit of time, which explains why it becomes difficult to see for

299
00:24:35,680 --> 00:24:40,400
several minutes after exposure to a very bright light.

300
00:24:40,400 --> 00:24:44,440
So the light sensors in your eyes are really just an elegant application of the concepts

301
00:24:44,440 --> 00:24:49,800
we've been discussing in this lecture.

302
00:24:49,800 --> 00:24:55,280
So I hope we can all agree now that structural and stereoisomerism make alkenes very interesting

303
00:24:55,280 --> 00:24:56,960
to us.

304
00:24:56,960 --> 00:25:00,540
Now it's time for alkynes to take the spotlight.

305
00:25:00,540 --> 00:25:05,160
We know from the geometry of a carbon-carbon triple bond that alkynes are not capable of

306
00:25:05,160 --> 00:25:10,200
that kind of stereoisomerism that makes alkenes so fascinating.

307
00:25:10,200 --> 00:25:13,200
But it doesn't make them uninteresting.

308
00:25:13,200 --> 00:25:20,080
Alkines have properties all their own which make them interesting to organic chemists.

309
00:25:20,080 --> 00:25:23,480
One very interesting property of alkynes is their acidity.

310
00:25:23,480 --> 00:25:28,240
Now it should be evident that internal alkynes don't have a very acidic proton since all

311
00:25:28,240 --> 00:25:33,280
of their hydrogens are on sp3 carbons, just like an alkane.

312
00:25:33,280 --> 00:25:40,360
The pKa of a terminal alkyne however is about 26, which may seem like a very weak acid and

313
00:25:40,360 --> 00:25:43,280
in fact it is.

314
00:25:43,280 --> 00:25:49,320
But compared to the acidity of alkenes with the pKa of 44 and of alkenes whose pKa is

315
00:25:49,320 --> 00:25:55,440
about 60, alkynes start to look like a pretty acidic compound.

316
00:25:55,440 --> 00:26:01,560
So at a pKa of 26, terminal alkynes are weak acids in the overall scheme of things but

317
00:26:01,560 --> 00:26:05,840
they are rock stars of acidity among hydrocarbons.

318
00:26:05,840 --> 00:26:10,680
In fact there are just a few bases available to us in the laboratory, albeit very strong

319
00:26:10,680 --> 00:26:16,240
ones which are capable of deprotonating terminal alkynes.

320
00:26:16,240 --> 00:26:21,320
Most notable of these is the amide ion, the conjugate acid of ammonia, which has a pKa

321
00:26:21,320 --> 00:26:23,480
of about 35.

322
00:26:23,480 --> 00:26:25,800
Easy to work with, no.

323
00:26:25,800 --> 00:26:28,400
But available, yes.

324
00:26:28,400 --> 00:26:33,640
So what's the source of the acidity in compounds like acetylene or propyne?

325
00:26:33,640 --> 00:26:38,440
The answer is that alkyne carbons are sp hybridized.

326
00:26:38,440 --> 00:26:44,360
Now heterolytically breaking the CH bond means that both bonding electrons will go to the

327
00:26:44,360 --> 00:26:46,540
carbon.

328
00:26:46,540 --> 00:26:54,240
This means that the hybrid orbital into which the bonding electrons go has about 50% s-character

329
00:26:54,360 --> 00:27:01,360
as opposed to about 33% s-character for an alkene and 25% s-character for an alkane.

330
00:27:04,480 --> 00:27:09,000
S orbitals hold their electrons tighter and closer to the nucleus than dupi orbitals of

331
00:27:09,000 --> 00:27:11,360
the same principal energy level.

332
00:27:11,360 --> 00:27:17,760
So a more s-character in a hybrid orbital means a more stable lone pair in that orbital.

333
00:27:17,760 --> 00:27:23,560
And a more stable conjugate base means a more acidic conjugate acid.

334
00:27:23,560 --> 00:27:28,800
These deprotonated alkynes are remarkably reactive compared to neutral hydrocarbons.

335
00:27:28,800 --> 00:27:33,240
And we'll see in a few lectures how these deprotonated alkynes can prove very useful

336
00:27:33,240 --> 00:27:39,480
reagents in the synthesis of other organic compounds.

337
00:27:39,480 --> 00:27:44,000
So far we've concerned ourselves with relatively simple, straight and branched alkenes and

338
00:27:44,000 --> 00:27:46,000
alkynes.

339
00:27:46,000 --> 00:27:51,440
But just as alkenes can be cyclic, so can alkenes and alkynes.

340
00:27:51,440 --> 00:27:55,960
In fact, we already saw an example of this during our discussion of chirality when we

341
00:27:55,960 --> 00:28:01,800
analyzed the stereochemistry of limony.

342
00:28:01,800 --> 00:28:06,640
Cyclic alkenes and cyclic alkynes follow many of the same rules as cyclic alkenes, but with

343
00:28:06,640 --> 00:28:08,640
two important considerations.

344
00:28:08,640 --> 00:28:13,960
First, just like with linear and branched hydrocarbons, the presence of the pi system

345
00:28:13,960 --> 00:28:18,640
usually makes them much more reactive than similar alkane counterparts.

346
00:28:18,640 --> 00:28:25,720
Second, the inclusion of a double bond with sp2 carbons and angles of about 120 degrees

347
00:28:25,720 --> 00:28:31,080
or a triple bond with sp carbons in a bond angle of about 180 degrees can significantly

348
00:28:31,080 --> 00:28:35,240
affect the ring strain of a cyclic hydrocarbon.

349
00:28:35,240 --> 00:28:38,920
Just take the example of cyclohexane.

350
00:28:38,920 --> 00:28:44,160
If we add a pi bond making cyclohexane, we create a molecule with bond angle strains

351
00:28:44,160 --> 00:28:49,240
forced upon it by the presence of four coplanar atoms from the alkene motif.

352
00:28:49,240 --> 00:28:54,480
Nonetheless, there are many examples of this motif in nature, including our familiar limony

353
00:28:54,480 --> 00:28:58,960
from the rinds of citrus fruits.

354
00:28:58,960 --> 00:29:04,560
Cyclicization of small alkenes also has the important effect of stabilizing the cis isomer.

355
00:29:04,560 --> 00:29:08,840
Recall that when we looked at linear alkenes, we saw how heats of combustion demonstrate

356
00:29:08,840 --> 00:29:14,680
that the trans isomer is more stable than the cis isomer.

357
00:29:14,680 --> 00:29:20,160
But in the case of cyclohexane, the trans isomer is impossible to make.

358
00:29:20,160 --> 00:29:24,080
So I've built a model here, including six atoms.

359
00:29:24,080 --> 00:29:29,720
And within these six atoms, I placed a single double bond here, one double bond.

360
00:29:29,720 --> 00:29:37,120
Now if I cyclize this with a cis double bond, I have a pretty good, pretty stable looking

361
00:29:37,120 --> 00:29:38,400
model here.

362
00:29:38,400 --> 00:29:41,960
Maybe not quite as good as cyclohexane, but pretty close.

363
00:29:41,960 --> 00:29:47,800
But what happens if I try to convert this double bond from a cis into a trans?

364
00:29:47,800 --> 00:29:53,320
Well in the case of a six-membered ring, I'm going to break my model kit.

365
00:29:53,320 --> 00:29:57,920
Notice how badly distorted this double bond is just to accommodate what I've attempted.

366
00:29:57,920 --> 00:30:03,440
It's essentially impossible to create this structure.

367
00:30:03,440 --> 00:30:07,920
In fact, in order to be able to create such a structure, a cyclic alkene that is in the

368
00:30:07,920 --> 00:30:11,360
trans confirmation requires at least seven atoms.

369
00:30:11,360 --> 00:30:15,200
Now here I have eight so that I don't break two model kits on one day.

370
00:30:15,200 --> 00:30:21,600
Again, very, very easy to create a cis alkene that looks fairly stable.

371
00:30:21,600 --> 00:30:31,520
But if I try to make the trans alkene, although I can, definitely doesn't look like a very

372
00:30:31,520 --> 00:30:32,840
happy molecule.

373
00:30:33,840 --> 00:30:35,840
Clearly there's additional ring strain.

374
00:30:35,840 --> 00:30:41,720
Many of my bonds are in poor bond angles and I've had to develop some new clashes from

375
00:30:41,720 --> 00:30:44,880
eclipsing interactions as well.

376
00:30:44,880 --> 00:30:50,680
So in the case of seven, eight, nine, or ten atoms, we can make the trans but not very

377
00:30:50,680 --> 00:30:51,680
stable.

378
00:30:51,680 --> 00:30:59,320
In fact, we have to get all the way to eleven atoms before we reach the point where a trans

379
00:30:59,320 --> 00:31:02,000
isomer is actually more stable once again.

380
00:31:02,800 --> 00:31:06,480
When we reach eleven atoms, we have enough conformational flexibility that my double

381
00:31:06,480 --> 00:31:10,760
bond in the trans configuration is tolerated very well.

382
00:31:10,760 --> 00:31:15,520
I can find lots of good stable conformations, which give it lots of room, and I don't break

383
00:31:15,520 --> 00:31:18,520
the double bond and I can reuse it later.

384
00:31:22,120 --> 00:31:23,640
Now take your model kit.

385
00:31:23,640 --> 00:31:26,040
Try to make cyclohexine.

386
00:31:26,040 --> 00:31:31,080
The 180 degree bond angle in the alkyne part of that system makes it almost geometrically

387
00:31:31,080 --> 00:31:34,440
impossible for this molecule to exist.

388
00:31:34,440 --> 00:31:39,920
I say almost because the carbon-carbon triple bond of an alkyne is about 20 percent shorter

389
00:31:39,920 --> 00:31:43,240
than a typical carbon-carbon single bond.

390
00:31:43,240 --> 00:31:48,600
Now this means that cyclohexine can theoretically exist and it probably does form as a high

391
00:31:48,600 --> 00:31:54,000
energy intermediate in certain reactions, but it can't be isolated and bottled like

392
00:31:54,000 --> 00:31:58,560
it's cyclohexene and cyclohexane cousins.

393
00:31:58,560 --> 00:32:01,760
Of course larger cyclic alkynes do exist.

394
00:32:01,760 --> 00:32:06,640
Cyclo-octyne for example is the smallest cyclic alkyne which is stable enough to be prepared

395
00:32:06,640 --> 00:32:08,640
and collected.

396
00:32:10,720 --> 00:32:16,080
So in this lecture we investigated how pi bonds change the chemistry of hydrocarbons.

397
00:32:16,080 --> 00:32:20,640
We took a look at how the geometry of the orbitals involved results in a weaker bond

398
00:32:20,640 --> 00:32:26,440
than their sigma-conner parts, but which restricts rotation about carbon-carbon bonds and also

399
00:32:26,440 --> 00:32:30,240
carbon-carbon triple bonds.

400
00:32:30,240 --> 00:32:36,320
We discussed alkenes, hydrocarbons containing double bonds, as well as alkynes, hydrocarbons

401
00:32:36,320 --> 00:32:38,540
containing triple bonds.

402
00:32:38,540 --> 00:32:43,200
We saw how these double and triple bonds are reactive and therefore are treated with higher

403
00:32:43,200 --> 00:32:47,720
priority in nomenclature than the simple alkyl substituents.

404
00:32:47,720 --> 00:32:52,960
We call these higher priority reactive motifs functional groups.

405
00:32:52,960 --> 00:32:57,560
We took a look at one of the great chemistry rivalries of all time, that between Markovnikov

406
00:32:57,560 --> 00:33:02,660
and Zetzev over trends in the stability of alkenes.

407
00:33:02,660 --> 00:33:06,840
We investigated how their work led to our understanding of trends in stability among

408
00:33:06,840 --> 00:33:13,640
various regio and stereoisomers of the same molecular formula.

409
00:33:13,640 --> 00:33:19,160
We took a look at how the function of a biologically relevant molecule, retinol, is tied to these

410
00:33:19,160 --> 00:33:25,520
trends in stability, that the spontaneous conversion of retinol from 11 cis to all trans

411
00:33:25,520 --> 00:33:31,120
conformations takes place when a photon temporarily breaks the associated pi bond.

412
00:33:31,120 --> 00:33:37,560
Next, we covered the unusual acidity of terminal alkynes and how the presence of a hydrogen

413
00:33:37,560 --> 00:33:43,520
on an SP-hybridized carbon is a rare structural feature which makes alkynes much more acidic

414
00:33:43,520 --> 00:33:46,120
than ordinary hydrocarbons.

415
00:33:47,120 --> 00:33:52,440
Finally, we investigated the effect of pi bonds on cyclic structures and how their presence

416
00:33:52,440 --> 00:33:58,400
can not only introduce cis transisomerization, but also chirality.

417
00:33:58,400 --> 00:34:04,000
We also saw how a clash of personalities in 1870s Russia led to a race to understanding

418
00:34:04,000 --> 00:34:09,560
alkene chemistry, which in turn helps us to arrive at a better understanding of the molecular

419
00:34:09,560 --> 00:34:12,520
mechanism of vision employed in modern medicine.

420
00:34:12,920 --> 00:34:15,320
We've had quite a journey this lecture.

421
00:34:17,320 --> 00:34:21,680
Next time, we will introduce a new class of atoms to the structural mix when we expand

422
00:34:21,680 --> 00:34:27,200
our inventory of compounds to include the halogens, fluorine, fluorine, bromine and

423
00:34:27,200 --> 00:34:31,800
iodine in a class of compounds called alkyl halides.

424
00:34:31,800 --> 00:34:32,800
I'll see you then.

